0 Diana Guzman is an angry young woman . Surviving an unrelenting series of disappointments and traumas , she takes her anger out on the closest targets.<br /><br />When she sees violence transformed and focused by discipline in a rundown boxing club , she knows she 's found her home . < br /><br />The film progresses from there , as Diana learns the usual coming - of - age lessons alongside the skills needed for successful boxing . Michelle Rodriguez is very good in the role , particularly when conveying the focused rage of a young woman hemmed in on all sides and fighting against not just personal circumstances but entrenched sexism.<br /><br />The picture could use some finesse in its direction of all the young actors , who pale in comparison to the older , more experienced cast . There are too many pauses in the script , which detracts from the dramatic tension . The overall quietness of the film drains it of intensity . < br /><br />This is a good picture to see once , if only to see the power of a fully realized young woman whose femininity is complex enough to include her power . Its limitations prevent it from being placed in the " see it again and again " category .
